<h1>@HI{{tokoro}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{tokoro}}</strong> @HI{{desu}}
<li> @Vte{{}} @HI{{iru}} <strong>@HI{{tokoro}}</strong> @HI{{desu}}
<li> @Vta{{}} <strong>@HI{{tokoro}}</strong> @HI{{desu}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@HI{{tokoro}} can mean a physical place, but in these constructions it has come to indicate a temporal position. In the
sentence patterns above, it means a specific point in time during the course of an action.
</br>

In @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{tokoro}}</strong> the meaning is that the action is about to start.
</br>

In @Vte{{}} @HI{{iru <strong>tokoro</strong>}} the meaning is that the action is happening now.
</br>

In @Vte{{}} <strong>@HI{{tokoro}}</strong> the meaning is that the action has just been completed.
</br>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    A: @HI{{@KJ{{daytime}}go@KJ{{meal}}ha mou @KJ{{eat}}mashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    B: @HI{{iie, korekara @KJ{{eat}}beru <strong>tokoro</strong>desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    A: Have you had lunch yet?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    B: No, I'm just about to have it now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    A: @HI{{@KJ{{happenstance^hinder}}no @KJ{{meadow^cause}}ga wakarimashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    B: @HI{{iie, @KJ{{now tune}}bete iru <strong>tokoro</strong>desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    A: Do you know what caused the breakdown?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    B: No, We are investigating it at the moment.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{tatta@KJ{{now}} @KT{{basu}}ga @KJ{{exit}}ta <strong>tokoro</strong>desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The bus left just now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>


<h2> Notes </h2>

@HI{{<strong>tokoro</strong>desu}} is a noun sentence and can be used in various structures.
